headline: Charles de Gaulle resigns as a head of a French provisional government.
Last Polish troops surrender
Gen Eisenhower welcomed in Hague (on Hitler's train)
The Prussian Academy of Sciences is founded with Gottfried Leibniz as president.
Battle of Viciosa (Monte Claros): English & Portuguese army beat Spain
Catalan Revolt (Guerra dels Segadors) breaks out in Catalonia.
English Lord Protector Oliver Cromwell bans Anglicans.
Henri IV crowned king of France
The Juan Fernández Islands in the South Pacific Ocean are discovered by Spanish sailor Juan Fernández.
French King Louis XIII declared an adult at 13
Polish parliament selects monarch August of Saxony as king

The Duke of Alba is sent to the Netherlands with a strong Spanish force to suppress unrest there. He replaces Margaret of Parma as Governor of the Netherlands. Prince William of Orange is outlawed, and Lamoral, Count of Egmont imprisoned.
Robert, Earl of Essex, leads revolt in London against Queen Elizabeth
(or 19) – The Portuguese galleon Madre de Deus, laden with treasure, is captured by English privateers in the Azores.
Anne Boleyn, second queen of Henry VIII of England, is arrested on the grounds of incest, adultery, and treason.
Battle of Flodden Fields; English defeat James IV of Scotland

Charles X Gustav succeeds his cousin Christina on the Swedish throne. After her abdication on the same day, Christina, now the former reigning queen of a Protestant nation, secretly converts to Catholicism.
Queen Isabella I of Spain signs her testament
–July 1 – Action of San Mateo Bay: English privateer Richard Hawkins in the Dainty is attacked and captured by a Spanish squadron off Esmeraldas, Ecuador.
Frances Drake completes circumnavigation of the world, sailing into Plymouth aboard the Golden Hind
